                  SECT. II. Traditions againſt Scripture.
                  IT is not to be imagined that the ſame word of God, which ſpeakes for all other truths, ſhould not ſpeake for it ſelfe; how fully doth it diſplay it's owne ſufficiencie and perfection.2. Tim, 3.16. All Scripture (ſaith the Choſen Veſſell) is giuen by inſpiration of God; and is profitable for doctrine, for reproofe, for correction, for inſtruction in righteouſneſſe. Profitable,Bellar. de verbo Dei, l. 4. c. 10.
                      ſaith the Cardinall, but not ſufficient; Many things may auaile to that end whereto they ſuffice not; So meat is profitable to nouriſh, but without naturall heat it nouriſheth not: Thus hee. Heare yet what followeth.2. Tim. 3.17. That the man of God may bee perfited, and thorowly furniſhed vnto all good workes. Loe it is ſo profitable to all theſe ſeruices, that thereby it perfects a Diuine; much more an ordiarie

Chriſtian: That which is ſo profitable, as to cauſe perfection, is abundantly ſufficient, and muſt needs haue full perfection in it ſelfe; That which can perfit the teacher, is ſufficient for the learner. The Scriptures can perfit the man of God, both for his calling in the inſtruction of others, and for his owne glorie.2. Tim. 3.15. 
